3. SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE

3.1 Overall Architecture

Our architecture employs a three-layer hierarchical design with horizontal integration across domains:

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    META-COORDINATION LAYER                   │
│  • Multi-objective conflict resolution                      │
│  • Dynamic resource allocation                              │
│  • System-wide optimization                                 │
│  Tools: Fuzzy Cognitive Maps, Reinforcement Learning, CBR   │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                    DOMAIN INTELLIGENCE LAYER                │
│  ┌─────────────┐  ┌─────────────┐  ┌─────────────┐        │
│  │ Optimization│  │ Maintenance │  │  Security   │        │
│  │ Engine      │  │ Engine      │  │  Engine     │        │
│  └─────────────┘  └─────────────┘  └─────────────┘        │
│         ▲              ▲              ▲                    │
├─────────┼──────────────┼──────────────┼────────────────────┤
│                    HYBRID AI ENGINE LAYER                   │
│  • Neuro-Fuzzy Systems                                     │
│  • Evolutionary Optimization                               │
│  • Multi-Agent Systems                                     │
│  • Digital Twin Integration                                │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

3.2 Hybrid AI Engine

3.2.1 Neuro-Fuzzy Systems

We employ Type-2 Adaptive Neuro-Fuzzy Inference Systems (ANFIS) that combine the learning capability of neural networks with the interpretability of fuzzy logic. Type-2 fuzzy sets handle higher-order uncertainty than traditional Type-1 systems.

Mathematical Formulation:

```
Rule i: IF x₁ is Aᵢ₁ AND x₂ is Aᵢ₂ ... THEN yᵢ = pᵢ₁x₁ + pᵢ₂x₂ + ... + rᵢ

Where:
• Aᵢⱼ are interval Type-2 fuzzy sets
• pᵢⱼ and rᵢ are consequent parameters learned via gradient descent
• Uncertainty is captured through footprint of uncertainty (FOU)
```

3.2.2 Evolutionary Optimization

Our Memetic Algorithm combines:

· Genetic Algorithm for global search
· Local Search (simulated annealing) for exploitation
· Fuzzy Adaptive Control for parameter tuning

Algorithm:

```
Initialize population P(0)
for generation t = 0 to T-1:
    Evaluate fitness of P(t)
    Select parents via tournament selection
    Apply crossover and mutation (rates adapted via fuzzy rules)
    Apply local search to elite individuals
    Update population P(t+1)
    Update Pareto archive
end for
Return non-dominated solutions
```

3.2.3 Digital Twin Integration

Each physical asset has a Cognitive Digital Twin with:

1. Physics-Based Model: First-principles equations
2. Data-Driven Model: Learned from operational data
3. Hybrid Model: Fusion of physics and data
4. Learning Engine: Continuous model updating

3.3 Domain Intelligence Layer

3.3.1 Optimization Engine

Multi-Objective Formulation:

```
Minimize: [f₁(x), f₂(x), ..., fₘ(x)]  
Subject to: gⱼ(x) ≤ 0, j = 1,...,J
            hₖ(x) = 0, k = 1,...,K
            x ∈ X

Where:
• fᵢ are objective functions (cost, efficiency, emissions, etc.)
• x includes continuous and discrete decision variables
• Constraints include operational, maintenance, and security
```

Key Features:

· Surrogate modeling for expensive objectives
· Constraint handling via fuzzy penalty functions
· Real-time adaptation to changing conditions

3.3.2 Maintenance Engine

Three-Stage Architecture:

1. Fault Detection: Autoencoders for anomaly detection
2. Diagnosis: Deep learning classifiers for fault identification
3. Prognosis: LSTM networks for Remaining Useful Life (RUL) prediction

Health Index Calculation:

```
HI(t) = w₁ × FD(t) + w₂ × TD(t) + w₃ × PD(t)

Where:
• FD(t): Feature deviation from normal
• TD(t): Trend degradation  
• PD(t): Probability of failure
• Weights wᵢ adapted via reinforcement learning
```

3.3.3 Security Engine

Multi-Layer Defense:

1. Physical Layer: Anomaly detection in sensor data
2. Network Layer: Intrusion detection in communications
3. Application Layer: Behavioral analysis of control commands
4. AI Layer: Protection against adversarial attacks

Threat Intelligence Fusion:

· Signature-based detection (known attacks)
· Anomaly-based detection (novel attacks)
· Threat intelligence feeds (external sources)
· Fuzzy correlation engine (alert fusion)

3.4 Meta-Coordination Layer

3.4.1 Conflict Resolution

Subsystems often have conflicting objectives (e.g., maintenance requires downtime while optimization requires continuous operation). Our Fuzzy Cognitive Map (FCM) approach models causal relationships:

```
C(t+1) = f(C(t) × W)

Where:
• C(t): Vector of concept activations at time t
• W: Weight matrix representing causal strengths
• f: Sigmoid activation function
```

3.4.2 Dynamic Resource Allocation

Resources (computational, energy, bandwidth) are allocated based on system state priority:

```
Allocationᵢ = Baseᵢ + Priority_Bonusᵢ - Penaltyᵢ

Priority determined by fuzzy rules:
IF Security_Threat IS High THEN Security_Priority = 1.0
IF Maintenance_Urgency IS Critical THEN Maintenance_Priority = 0.8  
ELSE Optimization_Priority = 0.6
```

3.4.3 Reinforcement Learning for Coordination

A multi-agent reinforcement learning system learns optimal coordination policies through interaction with the digital twin:

```
State: s = [Optimization_Score, Maintenance_Urgency, Security_Threat, ...]
Action: a = [Resource_Allocation, Priority_Setting, Constraint_Adjustment, ...]
Reward: r = α × Performance + β × Reliability - γ × Risk
```

