6.4 Limitations and Challenges

6.4.1 Technical Challenges

1. Integration Complexity: Combining multiple AI paradigms requires sophisticated engineering
2. Computational Overhead: Hybrid systems can be resource-intensive
3. Explainability Trade-offs: Balancing performance with interpretability remains challenging
4. Data Requirements: Need for diverse, high-quality training data
5. Standardization: Lack of standards for hybrid system interfaces

6.4.2 Organizational Challenges

1. Skill Gap: Need for "hybrid AI engineers" with cross-paradigm expertise
2. Change Management: Resistance to autonomous decision-making
3. Legacy Integration: Compatibility with existing systems
4. Governance: Establishing accountability for AI decisions
5. Regulatory Uncertainty: Evolving AI regulations and standards

6.4.3 Ethical Considerations

1. Autonomy vs. Control: Appropriate levels of human oversight
2. Bias Mitigation: Ensuring fairness across diverse operating conditions
3. Transparency Requirements: Meeting stakeholder expectations for explainability
4. Privacy Protection: Balancing data utilization with individual privacy
5. Accountability Frameworks: Determining responsibility for AI decisions

